	<div class="articles view" style="margin-top:18px;">
		<h1>Research Shows Poor Blood Vessel Function Could Lead to Alzheimerâ€™s: Are YOU at Risk?</h1>
		<div class="line"></div>
		<div class="bylineData">
			By <a href="/community/insider/william_v_judy_b_s_m_s_ph_d/5" title="Author profile: William V. Judy, B.S., M.S., Ph.D.">William V. Judy, B.S., M.S., Ph.D., Community Insider</a> -- 			Published:  December 30, 2010		</div>
		<br />
		<div>
		<div class="imwrap-left"><img src="/app/webroot/img/upload/wysiwyg/man-alzheimers.jpg" width="169" height="252" /></div>  It seems like every day we hear new reports on Alzheimer&rsquo;s research, some promising and some discouraging. One minute you may hear encouraging news about how to prevent Alzheimer&rsquo;s in the first place only to have hopes dashed&nbsp; by some other body of data. One thing scientists seem to agree on however, is that once the causes of Alzheimer&rsquo;s are identified finding better methods of treatment &ndash; and possibly prevention &ndash; are much more easily obtained.<br /><br />Once of the more recent reports points a finger at a condition widely known in the medical community for causing cardiovascular disease.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s called endothelium dysfunction and it&rsquo;s a problem with blood vessel linings &ndash; called endothelium &ndash; that may lead to the development of Alzheimer&rsquo;s.&nbsp; <br /><br /><i><b>What&rsquo;s bad for the heart is bad for the brain?</b></i><br /><br />In this dysfunction process the endothelium secretes protein substances that promote plaque formation in the vessels rather than the substances that prevent plaque build up.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s the earliest indicator of cardiovascular disease, but now scientists have learned that a poorly functioning endothelium affects the brain as well as the heart.<br /><br />In addition to unhealthy protein secretions, endothelium dysfunction also causes a loss of nitrous oxide in the lining of the blood vessels in the brain.&nbsp; Nitrous oxide helps prevent the narrowing of the vessels and helps deliver oxygen and nutrients to the brain. So, needless to say, it&rsquo;s vital that sufficient...<div align="center" class="bordered" style="margin-top: 10px;"><br />This Content is restricted to our Community.<br /><a href="/signin">Login</a> or <a href="/signup">Sign Up</a> for an account to continue reading!<br /><br /></div><br />		<br /><br />
				</div>
		<div class="clearer"></div>
