	"fulltext" => "Once of the more recent reports points a finger at a condition widely known in the medical community for causing cardiovascular disease.&amp;nbsp; It&amp;rsquo;s called endothelium dysfunction and it&amp;rsquo;s a problem with blood vessel linings &amp;ndash; called endothelium &amp;ndash; that may lead to the development of Alzheimer&amp;rsquo;s.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;b&gt;What&amp;rsquo;s bad for the heart is bad for the brain?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;In this dysfunction process the endothelium secretes protein substances that promote plaque formation in the vessels rather than the substances that prevent plaque build up.&amp;nbsp; It&amp;rsquo;s the earliest indicator of cardiovascular disease, but now scientists have learned that a poorly functioning endothelium affects the brain as well as the heart.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;In addition to unhealthy protein secretions, endothelium dysfunction also causes a loss of nitrous oxide in the lining of the blood vessels in the brain.&amp;nbsp; Nitrous oxide helps prevent the narrowing of the vessels and helps deliver oxygen and nutrients to the brain. So, needless to say, it&amp;rsquo;s vital that sufficient amounts are present. But it&amp;rsquo;s the increased production of proteins that cause the real damage as they contribute to the amyloid plaques commonly found in Alzheimer&amp;rsquo;s patients.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The most common risk factors for cardiovascular disease &amp;ndash; smoking, aging, sedentary lifestyle, high blood pressure, high cholesterol, diabetes &amp;ndash; all are linked to decreased nitric oxide.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The study included testing brain endothelial cells to determine if inhibiting the production of nitric acid would lead to the production of the unhealthy proteins in the endothelium.&amp;nbsp; What was found was an increase in these precursor proteins that eventually lead to production of the characteristic amyloid plaques seen in Alzheimer&amp;rsquo;s patients. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;b&gt;What&amp;rsquo;s good for the heart is good for the brain.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;It could very well be that keeping the walls of blood vessels healthy could help ward off cognitive impairment and eventually Alzheimer&amp;rsquo;s disease. Doctors have known for some time that healthy endothelium is crucial for heart health and those activities that contribute to endothelium health, such as exercise, are also good for an aging brain.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Exercise stimulates nitric oxide production in the endothelium which means the beneficial effects can be seen in the brain as well as the heart. Though exercise hasn&amp;rsquo;t been proven to prevent Alzheimer&amp;rsquo;s, research has shown that it can prevent or delay cognitive decline.",
